USA: Repetition is the mother of wisdom
It's funny how schoolboy-friendly Barack Obama, the president with the reputation of being the smartest, repeats the strategy of his predecessor, who he considered the stupidest, in the Afghan issue.
When he finally swallowed his long-awaited Afghan doctrine, it turned out that he had written it through a copy of Bush's Iraq script three years ago.
Not only does he use the word "as in Iraq" several times in the text itself, but he didn't hesitate to even use the title of Bush's January 2007 statement as the title of his own declaration: "A New Road Forward".
Three years ago, he himself criticized Bush's idea to send fresh troops to civil war-torn Iraq as "irresponsible and consequently disastrous".
But the months that followed showed that Bush's strategy based on the recommendations of the field commanders was the only possible and successful one, so much so that no news reports today mention Iraq at all.
Bush's reputation was not enhanced, but he left his successor objectively a much more grateful starting position than might have been expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama hopes that the miracle will happen again.
The increase in the military contingent was again requested by field commanders, most notably the senior commander of the Afghan operations General Stanley McCristal, who, despite his subordinate habits, harshly criticized the heavy shooters in the White House.
He asked for 40,000 men to help him turn things around.
The president hesitated for three months, but he couldn't think of anything better, so at least he cut the general off by 10,000 troops.
He managed to keep the promise of another 5,000 from Europe, although he had originally counted on at least 10.
The most problematic aspect of Obama's entire strategy seems to be his intention to begin withdrawing troops from Afghanistan in 18 months and complete the process in three years.
Many doubt that a halved increase will bear the same fruit as the Iraq process.
Despite the fraternal wars of recent years, Iraqi society is relatively well organized, its leaders honoring agreements.
The situation in Afghanistan is characterized by the opposite symptom - no one can be trusted and no agreements are being respected.
Under these conditions, the Afghan security forces are poorly prepared, accustomed to changing masters every day as they see fit.
Political institutions, even if formally established, will remain a post-tribal village, where patriarchal tribal relations will continue to flourish.
Balancing the interests of different ethnic groups is unusually difficult given the overlap in the relationship, which further complicates the Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Even building an "accessible state", which is the minimalist goal of the whole operation, doesn't seem very realistic.
The timeline of Obama's strategy is going to be a bit of a mess with his volunteerism.
Over the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only gotten worse and is now on the verge of explosion.
To believe that soldiers sent to warfare for the purpose of "a swift return home" will cause the miracle here performed, can only souls truly romantic, untouched by reality.
From a political point of view, setting a date for the withdrawal of troops is a clear irresponsibility, as the Taliban will see it as an indirect recognition of the American defeat.
The last NATO summit showed that the willingness of Europeans to participate in combat operations in Afghanistan is down.
European politicians cannot and do not want to explain to their constituents how the security of Germany or Italy is linked to the war in the Hindukush hills.
Another factor that could have a radical impact on the situation is the development of events around Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the increased sanctions against Iran are not affected, the United States will face a difficult question of whether to try to resolve the problem by military force.
The answer will be needed at a time when, according to Obama, America is moving toward a victorious withdrawal from Afghanistan.
However, any such solution will also be a dramatic turning point in the Afghan situation.
The only glue for Barack Obama is the fact that the presidential election is three years away, so there's still plenty of time left for him to come up with another strategy if it turns out to be a total failure.
