Czech discovery: substance that can even catch 'hardening' HIV viruses
A team of Czech and German scientists are testing new compounds that can slow the spread of HIV in the body.
The main advantage of the enhanced product is that it also takes on viruses that have already gained immunity to medicines.
This is a fact that in some cases prevails over the fact that the compound on a common variant of the virus is not as effective as some medicines already available.
AIDS is still incurable.
However, a mixture of medicines that prevent the spread of HIV in the body can significantly extend the life of patients.
However, their use is accompanied by a number of side effects.
In addition, incomplete suppression of the virus's propagation results in the development of so-called resistant viruses, against which drugs are no longer effective.
The work of experts from the three institutes of the Czech Academy of Sciences, the University of Prague and the University of Heidelberg opens the way to tackle resistance to the virus.
They have shown that substances called metalcarborates act on the protein responsible for the multiplication of HIV.
Metalocarbons are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds prevent the spread of the virus unlike any drug used today, and therefore they can overcome the problem of resistance.
In their work, scientists come up with new, improved compounds prepared based on knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to a viral protein.
Metalocarbonates have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-layer cages made up of boron, hydrogen, and carbon atoms are connected by a metal atom, in this case, cobalt.
A treacherous and resistant virus
HIV protease is an HIV virus protein that is essential to the life cycle of the virus.
Without HIV protease caused by the breakdown of HIV, no mature infectious virus particles would be produced.
By stopping HIV protease, we also stop the spread of the virus in the patient's body, the scientists explain in a press release issued by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Czech Academy of Sciences.
In a paper published in the Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, scientists describe a series of compounds in which two pairs of cells (see table) are connected by a short organic chain that is then systematically altered.
A little weaker, but more reliable
The effects of this series of substances against HIV protease have been tested in the test subject and against resistant (resistant) variants derived from HIV-infected patients.
The effect of metalcarborans on the normal enzyme variant is not as strong as in clinical medicinal products, but it does not lose its effect for resistant variants against which medicinal products are often ineffective.
The unique mechanism of action, as well as their other properties such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of further chemical treatment of both metalcarborans, make them interesting compounds for further research into the design of effective HIV drugs, says Pavlína Řezecová, Head of the Structural Biology Laboratory at the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry and the Institute of Molecular Genetics at the Academy of Sciences.
