This gives the process a great deal of flexibility, says John Coequyt, senior manager of the Sierra Club in Washington.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who designed the six-page document, is a 180-page abridgment of the text from the talks to focus on what the top UN climate official, Yvo de Boer, described as "the big picture".
It sets out the outlines for a possible agreement whereby the industrialized nations could jointly reduce their emissions by the year to 25 to 45 percent from 1990 levels, while the major developing countries could reduce their emissions to 15 to 30 percent during that period.
Together, the countries would cut emissions by 50 to 95 percent by 2050.
The European Union hastened to negotiate on Friday a pledge to provide $3.6 trillion over the next three years to help poorer countries adapt to climate change -- from managing flooding and drought to preventing deforestation.
But Friday still listed the same kind of verbal fireworks that prevailed in last week's interviews.
U.S. Special Envoy for Climate Change Todd Stern rejected a speech calling for binding greenhouse gas emissions cuts for industrialized countries compared to the willingness of major emerging economies if they were not financed by the developed world.
The move signaled that the Obama administration had imposed a tougher line against China by Bush administration officials just two years ago.
The United States will not join the treaty without transferring major developing countries and implementing actions, said Stern, who also complained that the text was not sufficient to secure the restrictions and should be reviewed by external observers.
Stern made the comment an hour after Chinese Deputy Foreign Minister He Yafei told the US chief climate negotiator that either a lack of "rural sense" or "extraordinary irresponsibility" had led earlier in the week to a statement that the United States would not provide financial assistance to China to deal with global warming.
With the future of the economic trajectory of the major world powers at stake, tensions have broken out both within the developing world and between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current struggle is mostly about preserving individual economies rather than the planet, between China and the United States about meeting their respective commitments, while poorer nations point out that two dozen of the world's most influential countries ignore the scientific imperative for more serious action.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said it was not surprising that major powers were fighting over who should bear the cost of limiting greenhouse gases, while vulnerable countries became much more aggressive in finding ways to prevent big emitters from acting responsibly.
It's clearly a game of new economic hegemony developing, said Ulate, who also serves as a regional climate change advisor in Mexico and Central America for international nature conservation.
Some of the countries most vulnerable to climate change have indicated that they would like to continue enforcing the legally binding agreement in Copenhagen, but most key participants said that the best outcome of the talks would be a political agreement.
The Alliance of Small Island States, which has 43 members, drafted a 24-page agreement last Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who led the international climate talks for the European Commission, said that the push by small island nations "has caused a political uproar to the entire policy process" in part because they are now united and demanding action from growing economies such as China and India.
Negotiations were called into question as delegates focused on the fact that they must resolve most of the remaining issues before the heads of government can negotiate a deal.
Senior officials such as Indian Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and Chinese Deputy Minister got off the planes and ran through the halls of the Bella Center to the closed doors of the meeting and new conferences so they could set out claims to be considered next week.
The full extent of the rally -- with 13,000 people moving in and out of the convention center every day, guitar-playing activists staging ironic late-night shows about the countries they thought sent them, and hand-to-hand paper rather than e-mail-driven proposals -- was challenged.
The intensity is only a superstition: almost all the key ministers were present in Copenhagen and 60 heads of state were previously in the centre.
We've gotten into the high categories, said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, said the deputy minister for global policy at the International Conservation Fund.
Weighing heavily.
The first British train at 140 miles per hour redefined this Monday feeling
At 5:13 a.m. on Monday morning, the whistles went dark on the train's departure sign, which marked the transport revolution in Britain.
The first high-speed passenger train in the country will reach a speed of 140 miles per hour and fly from Ashford, Kent to London's St Pancras, crossing the distance of 58 miles in 38 minutes.
Lord Adonis, Minister of Transport, then joined Mrs Kelly Holmes and joined the first high-speed passenger convoy outside London.
He hopes that the new service will eventually connect Britain to an international network of high-speed, reliable trains and connect the large Midlands, North and Scottish areas with London.
The absence of standing water should reduce travel times in passenger transport and on commercial roads and the transition from aircraft and cars to rail could reduce carbon emissions and eliminate road congestion.
Theoretically, the three major political parties have been persuaded to adopt this vision.
But the tens of billions of pounds needed to build a new national rail network, the inevitable battle for projects and concerns about environmental degradation have now halted the construction of Britain's high-speed railways.
High Speed Two (HS2), a company set up in January to provide the government with a feasible study, submitted its report to Lord Adonis on 30 December, the Times reported.
She provided him with a detailed map of the route of the next planned high-speed stage of the network.
The new London-West Midland route has been proposed within five metres of urban areas and neighbourhoods where access to the livelihood could be problematic.
In open landscape, a 25 m final route was planned.
HS2 also envisages three options for the extensive northbound high-speed network.
Lord Adonis will answer in the spring.
The preferred option is a Y-shaped configuration where one high-speed line should lead to West Midland.
The road should be divided near Birmingham with one branch running from the Pennines to Manchester and Scotland and the other running northeast to Sheffield, Leeds and Newcastle over Tyne.
One line should lead to Scotland.
"It seems that the most efficient choice has been made", said the railroad expert.
Once this is done, the travel time between London and Edinburgh will be reduced to two hours and 40 minutes.
The first stage, which will not open before 2025, could allow passengers to travel between London and Birmingham in 49 minutes compared to more than one hour in the present.
The proposals should allow trains to travel at 2250 miles per hour, making the UK network the fastest in Europe.
The initial route is already being designed to carry trains of 400 metres in length capable of carrying 1100 people.
Up to 18 files could operate every hour on the London-Birmingham route.
This means that the London terminal could handle up to 20,000 passengers per hour if necessary.
In view of the capital constraints, it is envisaged that the existing stations would be extended to include the high-speed network.
Railway industry experts claim that only San Pancras International or Euston offer such potential.
Lord Adonis will announce whether or not he intends to implement this scheme, but extensive public consultation and planning procedures mean that the final decision will not come before the general election.
Even if it moves the wheels, the grid should be built in pieces.
Trains should not be operated on high-speed lines first, but on existing lines north of Birmingham and should maintain travel times between London and Scotland above three hours.
This is considered a crucial point of contact for ensuring the transition from aircraft to trains, a landmark for the revolution on the railways.
Taxpayers have paid off a £75,000 mortgage on the Tory Orange
Alan Duncan, the Tory front-seat MP, was paid thousands of pounds by taxpayers last year for the orange house he built in his constituency home.
The prison party spokesman, who was demoted by David Cameron for complaining that MPs lived "from the earnings", raised his mortgage to £75,000 to build an oak-lined extension in his second house in Rutland.
He was allowed to charge a special interest, a total of hundreds of pounds a month to taxpayers.
The local authorities approved the claims in time and he was not interviewed by Sir Thomasen Legg, who was in charge of checking the membership's expenditure.
Mr Duncan, one of the wealthiest members of parliament, owns two two-storey houses in the villages of his constituency of Rutland and Melton.
The houses are worth about a million pounds.
There's a kitchen, living room and dining room on the ground floor, but the finance department has agreed that Mr. Duncan needs more space.
Last year, he added a winter garden to the house, which is designated an "orange garden".
Neighbors describe it as "a glass of fun and hospitality".
Mr. Duncan was not asked to provide any explanation for the increased loan during the final inspection by the Committee on Standards and Privileges in the last mortgage settlement.
The committee told him last month that he had violated the rules after reviewing his expenses.
In 2004, Mr Duncan changed his pupillary security to a mortgage of £27,1406 from his London estate to a house in his constituency he bought in 1991, a year before he became a member of the House of Commons.
Documents released this week show Mr Duncan was claiming approximately £1,400 a month in mortgage interest up to March last year.
In April, his claims increased to over £1,800 a month.
The interest rate on the RBS mortgage payment of Mr Duncan could not change during this time, which suggests that all this was intended to finance a loan of £75,000.
The standard variable RBS mortgage payment fell from 7,94% in December 2007 to 4% in March of this year, remaining at that level.
The last municipal records show Mr Duncan continued to claim £1,250 a month in May this year.
Mr. Duncan resigned as the shadow House leader in September after a secret report filmed him saying MPs must survive "on a share" after the spending scandal.
"It's basically nationalized, you have to live on a quota and you're being treated like a fucking asshole".
