75% of working mothers have work-related problems.
Employment discrimination has increased in recent years, particularly among younger women who are planning to have a child.
This is the result of the study 'Fertility and working career of Spanish women', carried out by CSIC in cooperation with the Women's Institute.
The study involved 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 and the results are clear: 75% of working mothers have limited opportunities in the labour market due to motherhood.
The study highlights that there are many differences in views on the number of children at the beginning of a partnership, depending on whether they work or not, and also depending on the type of employment.
Women who do not work outside the home, work part-time or do not have a stable job start living with their partner earlier, have their first child earlier and have more children overall.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, particularly in the public sector, partnership and motherhood are postponing and have fewer offspring.
'Women between the ages of 35 and 49 with stable employment have their first child on average 3.7 years after the start of their partnership.This figure is 4.1 for women who have spent most of their lives in stable employment and have therefore had to postpone their partnership and the birth of children.
The type of occupation also has a strong influence on motherhood, although less on the time of the start of life with the partner", explains Margarita Delgado, a CSIC researcher.
Another factor affecting the age of women at the time of marriage and the birth of of offspring is their education.
Research shows that the higher the level of education, the higher the age at which women marry and have their first child.
There are also differences between women of the same generation.
For example, in the age group of 35 to 49 years, women with primary and higher education had their first child at 25.1 or 32.1.
"There is another difference between women depending on their education.
Women with basic education marry and have their first child before they can find a stable job, while women with secondary or higher education who go on to the opposite end prefer to get a stable job before they marry and have their first child", says Delgado.
