The manual brake support system is now mandatory.
As with the ABS anti-lock system, ESP stability management and handbrake support systems will be compulsory equipment for European cars.
In fact, it already forms part of the mandatory equipment of all newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for others a deadline for removing the shortfall is set, which is February 2011.
The measures introduced in the EU aim to increase pedestrian protection, while working in a way that can help prevent many falls.
The manual brake support system increases the brake pressure in an emergency, which the system will detect after the driver has stepped down.
But he can't always keep up the pressure.
According to a study by Bosch, a car manufacturer, one third of the drivers who have an accident did not step on the brake before the crash and half of them did not use the brake force to their full potential.
Up to 1,100 accidents
On the contrary, this assistance requires the braking system to maximize, shortening the braking distance of the vehicle.
According to a study conducted in the EU alone, if all vehicles were equipped with this type of equipment, up to 1 100 pedestrian-related fatalities per year could be avoided.
The reduction in this number will be even more significant - according to the calculations, one in four accidents with a human impact would be prevented - after the introduction of so-called smart hand braking systems.
In this case, the vehicle shall be equipped with a system which (with the help of radar or cameras) detects and reports obstacles to the driver, except for light braking.
If the driver reacts, it will help to increase the pedal pressure if necessary.
If the driver does not react, even if the collision cannot be prevented, the equipment shall apply the braking force as minimally as possible and minimize the risk of damage.
